# Use Built-in react-chessboard Features

Always prefer the built-in options provided by `react-chessboard` instead of rolling custom SVG or DOM overlays on top of the board.

## Arrows

Use the `arrows` option (`Arrow[]`) to draw arrows on the board:

```typescript
<Chessboard
  options={{
    arrows: [{ startSquare: "e2", endSquare: "e4", color: "rgba(0, 120, 0, 0.8)" }],
  }}
/>
```

The `Arrow` type is `{ startSquare: string; endSquare: string; color: string }`.

**Do NOT** create custom SVG elements, `<svg>` overlays, or absolute-positioned layers to draw arrows on the chessboard.

## Square Highlights

Use `squareStyles` to highlight squares:

```typescript
squareStyles: { e4: { backgroundColor: "rgba(255, 255, 0, 0.4)" } }
```

## General Rule

Before implementing any visual overlay on the chessboard, check the `ChessboardOptions` type for a built-in option. Only use custom rendering if no built-in option exists.
